WEBVTT

00:01.302 --> 00:02.434
<i> Previously on "All Rise"...</i>

00:02.503 --> 00:03.435
I'm running for
State Attorney General.

00:03.504 --> 00:04.737
If you would look

00:04.805 --> 00:06.271
into Judge Benner's time
at Slefinger & Feste.

00:06.340 --> 00:08.540
I was hoping you could talk
to me about the Cuprillon case.

00:08.609 --> 00:10.209
Six months after we settled,

00:10.277 --> 00:13.078
an anonymous source leaked
internal docs--

00:13.147 --> 00:15.981
proof that Cuprillon knew
it was poisoning its workers

00:16.050 --> 00:17.416
and did nothing to stop it.

00:17.485 --> 00:19.451
- Have you met my son Ben?
- Your name is Ben Benner.

00:19.520 --> 00:20.953
I hope she doesn't get
too comfortable up there

00:21.022 --> 00:22.654
because it's not
gonna last.

00:22.723 --> 00:24.957
Palmer is leading a renegade
charge from the D.A.'s office

00:25.026 --> 00:27.426
claiming that you are judicially
biased towards your defendants.

00:27.495 --> 00:29.061
There was one thing
we weren't able to address--

00:29.130 --> 00:30.629
Travis Bolson.
What about him?

00:30.698 --> 00:32.331
- He died.
- Yes, he did.

00:32.400 --> 00:33.866
I love you.

00:36.303 --> 00:40.472
♪♪♪

00:40.541 --> 00:42.808
Okay, the only weird thing--

00:42.877 --> 00:45.144
Judge Benner
still doesn't know.

00:45.212 --> 00:47.713
Ben Benner hasn't told her yet,
which, I mean, thank God.

00:47.782 --> 00:49.248
I'm gonna need a strategy
to deal

00:49.316 --> 00:51.817
with that little piece
of awkwardness.
Ben Benner?

00:51.886 --> 00:53.652
I know, I know.
I'm calling him that now, too.

00:53.721 --> 00:55.387
Weird to think Judge Benner
could soon be

00:55.456 --> 00:56.989
dropping off muffins

00:57.058 --> 00:58.824
or whatever
your boyfriend's mother does.

00:58.893 --> 01:00.325
You have been
on two dates.

01:00.394 --> 01:03.495
Both of which I will remind you
went spectacularly well.

01:03.564 --> 01:04.930
Oh, I know. I heard.

01:04.999 --> 01:06.298
- Sorry.
- [ laughs ]

01:06.367 --> 01:08.300
No, it's okay.
It's just, I--I'm...

01:08.369 --> 01:10.936
I'm not sleeping again.

01:11.005 --> 01:12.871
It's 'cause of what Luke said.
That's why you're not sleeping.

01:12.940 --> 01:15.107
Those three gigantic words.
[ cellphone rings ]

01:15.176 --> 01:16.842
And there he is.

01:16.911 --> 01:19.611
You're avoiding him.
Of course I'm avoiding him,
Sara.

01:19.680 --> 01:22.648
[ cellphone chimes ]
I am freaking out.
I wanna run as fast as possible.

01:22.716 --> 01:24.716
What is wrong with me?
Oh, this is gonna be
good news.

01:24.785 --> 01:26.218
What is it?

01:26.287 --> 01:27.653
Uh, lawyer got a pummeling
from Judge Campbell,

01:27.721 --> 01:28.987
and now he wants
transcripts.

01:29.056 --> 01:31.056
- Hunting an appeal.
- Never gonna happen.

01:31.125 --> 01:33.058
But I will take his cash.
[ cellphone bloops ]

01:33.127 --> 01:34.359
- Boom.
- You know what?

01:34.428 --> 01:36.228
- I'm not gonna rush it.
- Exactly. Don't rush it.

01:36.297 --> 01:37.362
I mean, I have to catch up
on my casework.

01:37.431 --> 01:39.231
That is where my head
needs to be--my work.

01:39.300 --> 01:41.700
I don't have time
to consider whatever--

01:41.769 --> 01:44.069
whether I'm feeling--
which apparently I probably--

01:44.138 --> 01:45.704
You know what?
I'm not gonna think about it.

01:45.773 --> 01:47.139
I'm not thinking about it.

01:47.208 --> 01:49.508
♪♪♪

01:49.577 --> 01:51.410
Location check.
I need to know you're en route

01:51.479 --> 01:54.012
or parking or preferably
in the elevator right now.

01:54.081 --> 01:55.647
We're at T-minus 30 minutes.

01:55.716 --> 01:57.549
30 minutes to go time,
Your Honor.

01:57.618 --> 01:59.852
- Oh.
- Carmichael in yet?

01:59.920 --> 02:01.587
Judge Benner, good morning.
No.

02:01.655 --> 02:03.355
She's going to give me
her findings when she gets in.

02:03.424 --> 02:04.656
Oh, opposition research.

02:04.725 --> 02:06.291
Attorney General.
Exciting times.

02:06.360 --> 02:08.327
Full report, which I suspect
you could also give me,

02:08.395 --> 02:10.295
but I'd prefer to get it
from the horse's mouth.

02:10.364 --> 02:13.165
I will tell her
you are waiting and eager.

02:13.234 --> 02:14.433
Well, I wouldn't say
I'm eager.

02:14.502 --> 02:16.435
I just wouldn't think
it would take this long.

02:16.504 --> 02:17.769
[ clears throat ]

02:17.838 --> 02:20.839
And here you are!
That was predictable.

02:20.908 --> 02:23.842
Lisa, lovely morning.
Don't drink that.

02:23.911 --> 02:25.944
Oh. Thank you.

02:26.013 --> 02:28.647
So, any skeletons
in my closet?

02:28.716 --> 02:31.383
You have had, I must say,

02:31.452 --> 02:33.318
all in all
an exemplary career.

02:33.387 --> 02:35.354
Which is why I would make
an awesome Attorney General.

02:35.422 --> 02:37.389
I have the experience,
the vision.

02:37.458 --> 02:38.790
There's just one thing
we need to--

02:38.859 --> 02:39.825
Cuprillon Industries.

02:39.894 --> 02:42.227
Your first gig.
Private practice.

02:42.296 --> 02:44.163
A client with a workplace
that poisoned its workers.

02:44.231 --> 02:46.298
Your firm withheld
key documents.
A memo.

02:46.367 --> 02:47.900
- A memo.
- Yes.

02:47.968 --> 02:49.735
Which showed Cuprillon
knew about the toxicity

02:49.803 --> 02:51.136
and failed to act.

02:51.205 --> 02:52.738
Because you withheld
the documents,

02:52.806 --> 02:55.374
payouts were lower,
and workers got screwed.

02:55.442 --> 02:57.976
So it was two
of the senior partners,

02:58.045 --> 02:59.711
and when it came out,
they were disbarred.

02:59.780 --> 03:01.146
It's all
on the public record.

03:01.215 --> 03:04.082
The other seven of us
on the team had no clue

03:04.151 --> 03:06.251
what was going on.
You didn't know?

03:06.320 --> 03:07.586
I had no idea
the memo existed.

03:07.655 --> 03:09.021
None of us did,
not until later.

03:09.089 --> 03:12.191
Lisa, when it comes out,
and it almost certainly will,

03:12.259 --> 03:15.194
I'm not sure
anyone will believe that.

03:15.262 --> 03:17.496
[ scoffs ]
Well, let's start with you.

03:17.565 --> 03:18.864
With me?

03:18.933 --> 03:20.766
Do you believe me?

03:20.834 --> 03:23.335
♪♪♪

03:23.404 --> 03:26.338
Sam! I need the LAPD thing
on the thing. I need it printed.

03:26.407 --> 03:28.473
I think he's talking to you.

03:28.542 --> 03:29.975
He's not talking.
He's yelling.

03:30.044 --> 03:31.210
Did you change your name
in the last 10 minutes?

03:31.278 --> 03:33.445
I should go print out
the thing on the thing.

03:33.514 --> 03:34.846
I wasn't yelling.
I was employing volume.

03:34.915 --> 03:37.382
Right.
Callan, how's it going
with Teflon Mitch?

03:37.451 --> 03:39.184
- Heard you were tanking it.
- I'm not tanking it.

03:39.253 --> 03:41.053
Our case went extremely well,
did it not, Sam?

03:41.121 --> 03:43.322
Mm-hmm, sure.
So he hasn't taken
the stand yet.

03:43.390 --> 03:45.791
It's over. Soon as he does,
you're done. I've been there.

03:45.859 --> 03:47.159
Yeah, me, too.
Juries love him.

03:47.228 --> 03:49.228
Nothing sticks
to this guy<i> ever.</i>

03:49.296 --> 03:50.462
His lawyer's almost done
presenting her case.

03:50.531 --> 03:51.830
He won't testify.
Oh, yes, he will.

03:51.899 --> 03:52.831
The man will take the stand.

03:52.900 --> 03:53.832
- Teflon Mitch?
- Choi.

03:53.901 --> 03:55.133
Be ready to cut a deal.

03:55.202 --> 03:57.536
Hey, I can handle
Teflon Mitch.

03:57.605 --> 03:58.904
Let's get our things
together.

03:58.973 --> 04:00.038
Did you see how quietly
I said that?

04:00.107 --> 04:01.506
Yet I heard every word.

04:01.575 --> 04:04.176
So you're my guy today.
Let's go. I need coffee.

04:04.245 --> 04:06.511
Your guy? Really?
You're gonna listen,
and you're gonna learn--

04:06.580 --> 04:07.980
a crash course
in real lawyering.

04:08.048 --> 04:09.681
Disregard everything
you learned in law school.

04:09.750 --> 04:11.683
I am your education.

04:13.354 --> 04:15.087
You know everything that
happens in this courthouse.

04:15.155 --> 04:17.789
I don't.
At every moment,
on every floor.

04:17.858 --> 04:19.825
Half the time, you know what I'm
thinking before I even think it.

04:19.893 --> 04:21.593
Say it, Carmichael.
That's why we're here.

04:21.662 --> 04:24.529
You were a junior associate
reviewing documents.

04:24.598 --> 04:26.665
Wouldn't you be
the first person to know?

04:26.734 --> 04:28.634
Because if you did know

04:28.702 --> 04:32.304
and if you stood by
while those workers...

04:34.074 --> 04:36.642
Then I think you might
be in trouble.

04:39.780 --> 04:41.446
[ sighs ]

04:47.121 --> 04:49.721
What if I didn't stand by?

04:49.790 --> 04:51.023
Meaning?

04:51.091 --> 04:53.492
What if, when I found out
what was going on

04:53.560 --> 04:54.993
and I couldn't sleep
at night,

04:55.062 --> 04:57.462
what if, late one night,
3 a.m.,

04:57.531 --> 05:01.566
what if I went
into the office

05:01.635 --> 05:02.901
and made copies?

05:04.405 --> 05:07.973
It was you?
You leaked the memo?

05:08.042 --> 05:10.742
I couldn't sleep.
[ sighs ]

05:10.811 --> 05:12.744
I had to do something.

05:12.813 --> 05:15.681
♪♪♪

05:15.749 --> 05:17.349
I've got literally
two minutes.

05:17.418 --> 05:19.418
How's Teflon Mitch going?

05:19.486 --> 05:22.654
- It's going badly.
- Has he testified yet?

05:22.723 --> 05:25.190
Why does everyone want--
You are doomed, Mark.
Admit it.

05:25.259 --> 05:27.025
Okay, what is it
about liars and con men

05:27.094 --> 05:30.162
that everyone finds so charming,
they give 'em a pass?
Whoa, slow down.

05:30.230 --> 05:32.164
Anyway,
what did you want to...

05:32.232 --> 05:34.199
You're doing that thing
with your jaw. What's wrong?

05:34.268 --> 05:35.834
Wait. What?
There's no jaw thing.

05:35.903 --> 05:37.936
- Lola.
- It's Judge Benner.

05:38.005 --> 05:40.505
- Your opposition research?
- Yeah. Kinda didn't go great.

05:40.574 --> 05:42.374
What did I tell you?
I told you it would

05:42.443 --> 05:43.875
bite you in the ass.
Bite me in the ass.

05:43.944 --> 05:45.777
- What'd you find?
- A big ol' ethical violation.

05:45.846 --> 05:47.546
- How big?
- I don't know, like big enough

05:47.614 --> 05:49.948
to get her thrown off the bench.
That kind of big.

05:50.017 --> 05:51.483
I cannot tell you
what it is.

05:51.552 --> 05:53.218
But she did it
for the right reasons,

05:53.287 --> 05:54.619
but it won't matter
because...

05:54.688 --> 05:57.022
[ exhales deeply ] she cannot
run for Attorney General.

05:57.091 --> 05:58.557
Have you
told her that yet?

05:58.625 --> 06:01.093
Hell, no.
It's bad, Mark.

06:01.161 --> 06:03.161
Whatever it is,
she's not going to withdraw.

06:03.230 --> 06:04.596
You'll just make an enemy
of her,

06:04.665 --> 06:07.165
and you'll end up
paying the price.

06:07.234 --> 06:08.967
Hey, I mean it, Lo.

06:09.036 --> 06:11.570
You need to get out
of this now.

06:14.541 --> 06:17.576
Captioned by
Los Angeles Distribution
and Broadcasting, Inc.

06:19.511 --> 06:23.113
♪♪♪

06:23.182 --> 06:24.681
Sorry. Thanks.

06:24.750 --> 06:25.882
Andy, what's going on?

06:25.951 --> 06:28.051
I just got a semi-hysterical
text from Carol.

06:28.120 --> 06:29.686
- Uh...
- Emily, there you are. Good.

06:29.755 --> 06:32.822
I'm in crisis mode right now.
I have a situation with Barry.

06:32.891 --> 06:34.324
Whoa! Are you okay?

06:34.393 --> 06:35.892
- Yeah, I'm--I'm fine.
- Okay.

06:35.961 --> 06:37.794
Sorry. Watch your step.

06:37.863 --> 06:39.329
Barry's taking--
well, he suddenly announced

06:39.398 --> 06:40.864
he's taking
sudden retirement.

06:40.933 --> 06:42.199
- When?
- Today.

06:42.267 --> 06:44.968
- No.
- Yes, my most senior deputy.

06:45.037 --> 06:46.136
On the phone with him
right now.

06:46.205 --> 06:47.470
He's literally weeping.

06:47.539 --> 06:50.807
It's okay. I have him on mute.
Here. Can you...

06:50.876 --> 06:53.143
Um...
I need to redistribute
his entire caseload.

06:53.212 --> 06:55.412
He has four matters
on calendar today.

06:55.480 --> 06:57.914
We'll split them between us.
Careful. Sorry.
Watch your step.

06:57.983 --> 06:59.950
Meet me in 802
in 10 minutes.

07:00.018 --> 07:02.652
Okay, honey, I know. Uh-huh.

07:02.721 --> 07:04.254
But I have an office day!
[ door closes ]

07:04.323 --> 07:05.322
[ whimpers ]

07:05.390 --> 07:07.824
Her name is Patrice.
30s, probably drunk.

07:07.893 --> 07:09.659
I can't read Barry's writing.
Is that a 7?

07:09.728 --> 07:12.963
Um...Patrice. Patrice?
Are you Patrice?

07:13.031 --> 07:14.598
- Sure.
- Carol. I'm the new Barry.

07:14.666 --> 07:15.932
Whew. You smell like gin,
my dear.

07:16.001 --> 07:17.601
Let's get you some mouth spray.
Here we go.

07:17.669 --> 07:19.202
This file is a total disaster.

07:19.271 --> 07:20.937
Your client isn't
the victim.

07:21.006 --> 07:22.005
This is what rookies
don't understand,

07:22.074 --> 07:23.273
and it isn't the D.A.

07:23.342 --> 07:24.507
or God knows
whatever random judge

07:24.576 --> 07:26.176
they happen to assign to you
because you're not--

07:26.245 --> 07:27.844
Sorry. I'm sorry.
I'll catch up. Two minutes.

07:27.913 --> 07:29.846
- I'll give you one.
- Hey, Em.

07:29.915 --> 07:31.381
"Menial hearse coupe."
What does that even mean?

07:31.450 --> 07:33.617
- I take them back.
- What?

07:33.685 --> 07:34.851
Those three unfortunate words--
let's just say

07:34.920 --> 07:36.019
they never happened
so that maybe

07:36.088 --> 07:37.287
you could stop
avoiding me now?

07:37.356 --> 07:39.723
Metal--Metal head--
Oh! Mental health court.

07:39.791 --> 07:41.391
Oh,
this will be a first.

07:41.460 --> 07:43.360
Luke, I need--I'm supposed
to be downstairs, like, now.

07:43.428 --> 07:44.828
I thought you didn't
have court today.

07:44.896 --> 07:48.031
Barry decided to retire,
like, today. Total nightmare.

07:48.100 --> 07:50.500
Barry? Really?
Let's talk about them later,
okay?

07:50.569 --> 07:52.502
The three--The words--
The three little words, okay?

07:52.571 --> 07:54.304
I promise!

07:54.373 --> 07:57.007
Judge: All right, counsel,

07:57.075 --> 07:59.242
I'll be looking for updates
on her progress.

07:59.311 --> 08:02.178
You tell her that I have
big plans for her.

08:02.247 --> 08:04.147
- She loves you, Your Honor.
- [ chuckles ]

08:04.216 --> 08:05.649
I mean, she goes mad.

08:05.717 --> 08:06.783
She better not.

08:06.852 --> 08:08.118
She needs to buckle down
and get better.

08:08.186 --> 08:09.953
- Rae Lynn Wiggins?
- Yes.

08:10.022 --> 08:12.522
Hi. I'm Emily Lopez.
I'm filling in for Barry today.

08:12.591 --> 08:14.924
Hi. Oh, you look like
a nice lawyer.

08:14.993 --> 08:16.493
Oh. Thank you.

08:16.561 --> 08:19.162
Okay, let's move on.
<i>The People vs. Rae Lynn Wiggins.</i>

08:19.231 --> 08:21.698
Emily Lopez, Your Honor,
for Ms. Wiggins.

08:21.767 --> 08:24.934
Ms. Lopez, your first time here.
You may join the circle.

08:25.003 --> 08:29.105
And there's Rae Lynn.
It's so nice to see you again.

08:29.174 --> 08:30.340
Hi, Your Honor.

08:30.409 --> 08:31.808
Uh...Ms. Wiggins has

08:31.877 --> 08:33.443
a proof of progress report

08:33.512 --> 08:35.278
from her mental health
treatment program.

08:35.347 --> 08:37.047
Sure, sure. Give it to Marcy.

08:37.115 --> 08:40.550
Rae Lynn, talk to me.
How are you doing?

08:40.619 --> 08:42.218
Thanks.
I...

08:42.287 --> 08:44.521
completed the program.

08:44.589 --> 08:47.891
You did?
Oh, well done, everybody.

08:47.959 --> 08:51.528
[ applause ]

08:51.596 --> 08:53.029
That's so great.

08:53.098 --> 08:55.198
Come here, sweetie.

08:55.267 --> 08:57.901
They said
I did really well.

08:57.969 --> 08:59.903
[ gasps ] Oh.

09:00.906 --> 09:01.971
I'm very proud of you.

09:02.040 --> 09:03.340
Keep going, okay?

09:03.408 --> 09:05.041
Good job, good job.

09:12.250 --> 09:13.783
Transcription?

09:13.852 --> 09:15.819
Uh-huh, from one of scary
Judge Campbell's cases

09:15.887 --> 09:17.687
that's getting appealed.
They're actually--

09:17.756 --> 09:21.658
No! From the deli!
Pastrami on rye

09:21.727 --> 09:24.094
from the fatty end
with the special mustard.

09:24.162 --> 09:26.296
- Man: Yes, Judge Campbell.
- Thank you.

09:31.169 --> 09:32.602
Something wrong?

09:32.671 --> 09:34.637
With the transcript?
- Huh?

09:34.706 --> 09:36.039
No, nothing.

09:36.108 --> 09:41.177
♪♪♪

09:41.246 --> 09:43.446
[ laughter ]

09:43.515 --> 09:46.149
Right? Right? So look,
I'm trying to be an actor.

09:46.218 --> 09:48.351
But honestly,
I'm so terrible, guys.

09:48.420 --> 09:50.220
- Jury: Aw.
- No, no, no. I am.

09:50.288 --> 09:51.554
The point is,
I had an audition

09:51.623 --> 09:53.356
to be a giant banana
in a pudding commercial.

09:53.425 --> 09:55.625
This is a true story.
- And this was at what time?

09:55.694 --> 09:57.627
This is 8 p.m., although I was
supposed to be done at 6,

09:57.696 --> 09:59.062
but they were behind,
like, hours,

09:59.131 --> 10:00.530
and I had a date at 8:30.

10:00.599 --> 10:01.831
Objection, Your Honor.
Relevance.

10:01.900 --> 10:03.900
Uh, overruled.
I want to hear how this ends.

10:03.969 --> 10:06.136
First date--I don't have time
to go home and change,

10:06.204 --> 10:09.005
and I am head to toe
banana yellow.

10:09.074 --> 10:10.340
[ laughter ]
But then I get there...

10:10.409 --> 10:12.208
This is what they were
talking about, right here.

10:12.277 --> 10:14.310
No kidding.
She's in full yellow,
like it was in the stars.

10:14.379 --> 10:15.912
Needless to say,
we--we stood out.

10:15.981 --> 10:17.480
[ laughter ]
Nothing further, Your Honor.

10:17.549 --> 10:18.915
Mr. Callan, your witness.

10:18.984 --> 10:20.550
Mr. Sanderly, is it not true

10:20.619 --> 10:22.352
that you were caught
selling on eBay,

10:22.421 --> 10:23.887
a necklace stolen
from the victim's house?

10:23.955 --> 10:26.322
I found that in a flea market.
I had no idea it was stolen.

10:26.391 --> 10:28.892
And the security video
from the house?

10:28.960 --> 10:30.760
People's exhibit 3,
which we all watched.

10:30.829 --> 10:33.163
Did it not show a man with
the exact same build as you?

10:33.231 --> 10:35.165
Some other guy
with the same build.

10:35.233 --> 10:37.100
I was at Indigo Tavern
in full yellow.

10:37.169 --> 10:38.535
You couldn't miss me.

10:38.603 --> 10:40.603
And then my date lasted
till 9 a.m. the next morning

10:40.672 --> 10:42.172
despite the banana,

10:42.240 --> 10:44.107
or maybe because of it.
I don't know.

10:44.176 --> 10:46.242
[ laughter ]
I'm sorry.
Which restaurant?

10:46.311 --> 10:48.278
Indigo Tavern.
Little hole in the wall

10:48.346 --> 10:50.380
in Koreatown, strip mall.

10:50.449 --> 10:51.714
It's one of the best secrets
in all of L.A.

10:51.783 --> 10:53.616
I've been going there
literally for 15 years.

10:57.689 --> 10:59.556
Mr. Callan, hello!

10:59.624 --> 11:01.991
Yeah, uh, yes.

11:02.060 --> 11:03.893
Your Honor,
may I approach the bench?

11:07.933 --> 11:10.834
I apologize
for the late notice.

11:10.902 --> 11:13.803
I just remembered
something important.

11:13.872 --> 11:16.206
A doctor's appointment...

11:16.274 --> 11:19.042
in Santa Monica.

11:19.110 --> 11:20.410
Any chance we could,
uh...

11:21.980 --> 11:23.379
Recess. Back tomorrow.

11:23.448 --> 11:29.085
♪♪♪

11:29.154 --> 11:30.420
All right,
so eight years ago,

11:30.489 --> 11:32.555
I'm working second chair
on a murder trial.

11:32.624 --> 11:33.890
Big house
up in Laurel Canyon.

11:33.959 --> 11:35.358
Two brothers
who live together.

11:35.427 --> 11:37.093
One of the brothers,
Douglas,

11:37.162 --> 11:39.229
was convicted of killing
the other brother Troy.

11:39.297 --> 11:40.697
However, Douglas always
maintained his innocence.

11:40.765 --> 11:42.198
What does this have to do
with Teflon Mitch?

11:42.267 --> 11:43.700
I'm trying to tell you.
Douglas claimed

11:43.768 --> 11:45.268
that an intruder
killed his brother,

11:45.337 --> 11:46.903
that Troy heard someone
in the house,

11:46.972 --> 11:48.204
went downstairs with--

11:48.273 --> 11:50.440
he kept a gun
in his bedside table.

11:50.509 --> 11:51.741
Here it is. As second chair,
it was my job

11:51.810 --> 11:53.009
to keep track
of the evidence,

11:53.078 --> 11:54.511
some of which we didn't
end up using.

11:54.579 --> 11:56.713
Can you guess why?
'Cause it didn't fit
your narrative.

11:56.781 --> 11:59.048
Somebody had been smoking
cigarettes in the backyard.

11:59.117 --> 12:00.517
We assumed it was
one of the brothers,

12:00.585 --> 12:03.052
but it could've been--
The intruder
casing the place.

12:04.356 --> 12:07.090
That's the restaurant
that...

12:09.261 --> 12:10.493
So what, you're saying

12:10.562 --> 12:12.328
that Troy was murdered
by Teflon Mitch?

12:12.397 --> 12:14.497
I'm not saying anything.

12:14.566 --> 12:17.333
But Mitch has been breaking
into houses at least that long.

12:17.402 --> 12:19.135
He would make that kind
of a mistake?

12:19.204 --> 12:21.371
Dropping the matchbook?
I don't know.
Eight years ago, maybe.

12:21.439 --> 12:24.407
So Troy heard Mitch

12:24.476 --> 12:26.543
and came downstairs
with the gun.

12:26.611 --> 12:28.645
- Struggled for the weapon.
- And Troy ended up dead.

12:29.981 --> 12:32.382
Which means the wrong guy
is in prison.

12:32.450 --> 12:33.683
I'm not saying that yet.

12:33.752 --> 12:35.418
I'm saying that we need
to follow up.

12:35.487 --> 12:38.688
Homicide detective's name
was Parilla. Call him.

12:38.757 --> 12:40.490
We're gonna need
some photos.

12:40.559 --> 12:44.861
♪♪♪

12:44.930 --> 12:46.930
Sorry I'm late.
Just getting up to speed

12:46.998 --> 12:48.364
on some of Barry's cases.

12:48.433 --> 12:50.066
We're gonna start
from scratch.

12:50.135 --> 12:51.668
Talk me through
the incident, Tommy.

12:53.471 --> 12:54.904
It was a bar fight?

12:54.973 --> 12:56.539
If that's what you call
hitting a guy over the head

12:56.608 --> 12:58.074
with a half-filled
bottle of bourbon,

12:58.143 --> 12:59.375
sending him to the hospital.

12:59.444 --> 13:00.977
This guy?

13:01.046 --> 13:03.479
Oh, God.

13:03.548 --> 13:05.114
Man, that's--ahem--
Hadn't seen that.

13:05.183 --> 13:06.416
That's brutal.

13:08.253 --> 13:10.486
You lost your temper,
Tommy?

13:10.555 --> 13:13.022
He was drunk,
harassing a waitress.

13:13.091 --> 13:15.058
It's not an excuse.

13:15.126 --> 13:17.727
22 stitches. Concussion.
No permanent damage.

13:17.796 --> 13:20.997
You've got two prior assaults
on your record,

13:21.066 --> 13:23.666
both misdemeanors,
but this is a felony.

13:23.735 --> 13:24.901
That means a first strike,
Tommy.

13:24.970 --> 13:26.569
Four years in jail.
Yeah, I know.

13:28.573 --> 13:29.739
You're ex-military.

13:29.808 --> 13:32.175
1st Battalion.
6th Marines. Afghanistan.

13:32.243 --> 13:33.676
You were in combat?

13:37.983 --> 13:40.550
No steady job.
Keep getting in bar fights?

13:40.619 --> 13:41.851
When I drink.

13:41.920 --> 13:44.087
I should drink less.
A lot less.

13:49.594 --> 13:50.927
Tommy, is it possible

13:50.996 --> 13:52.996
that you're having
a hard time

13:53.064 --> 13:55.865
dealing with...
with your time in combat?

13:55.934 --> 13:58.334
Is that why this
keeps happening?

14:00.105 --> 14:03.373
I'm asking, Tommy,
if it's possible

14:03.441 --> 14:05.942
that you have
post-traumatic stress disorder.

14:07.712 --> 14:08.878
I mean, probably.

14:08.947 --> 14:10.813
The V.A. thinks I do.

14:10.882 --> 14:13.116
They gave you a diagnosis?

14:13.184 --> 14:15.051
[ scribbling ]

14:15.120 --> 14:16.819
Did they give you
any treatment? Medication?

14:16.888 --> 14:18.121
Honestly, I've just--

14:18.189 --> 14:20.890
[ exhales ] I'm trying
to move on with my life.

14:20.959 --> 14:23.826
- For the last six years?
- Yeah.

14:23.895 --> 14:26.663
How's that working out
for you?

14:29.034 --> 14:31.901
Barry was gonna
plead you out.

14:31.970 --> 14:33.536
I have a better idea.

14:33.605 --> 14:36.139
♪♪♪

14:36.207 --> 14:37.907
Keep an eye on the judge,
the defendant.

14:37.976 --> 14:39.475
Body language,
facial expressions.

14:39.544 --> 14:40.843
If you have a thought,
write it down.

14:40.912 --> 14:42.178
I don't like
to be interrupted.

14:42.247 --> 14:43.513
First time
in Judge Carmichael's courtroom

14:43.581 --> 14:45.982
since you tried to get her
fired. Are you worried?

14:46.051 --> 14:49.085
Why do you think you're here?
She loves you.

14:49.154 --> 14:51.487
That's our victim.
Stay here.

14:51.556 --> 14:52.622
Hey.

14:54.159 --> 14:55.324
Great. You're here.

14:55.393 --> 14:56.959
I just have
some final questions.

15:00.899 --> 15:02.031
What are you doing here?

15:02.100 --> 15:03.366
You were supposed
to be Barry.

15:03.435 --> 15:04.801
[ door opens ]
All rise.

15:04.869 --> 15:06.669
Department 61
of L.A. Superior Court

15:06.738 --> 15:08.204
is now in session.

15:08.273 --> 15:10.339
Judge Lola Carmichael
presiding.

15:10.408 --> 15:12.008
You may be seated.

15:12.077 --> 15:16.279
Uh, Mr. Watkins,
welcome to the show.

15:16.347 --> 15:17.346
Thank you, Your Honor.

15:17.415 --> 15:19.582
New uniform looks good on you.

15:26.691 --> 15:29.726
<i> People vs. Thomas Farrell.</i>
Counsel, your appearances.

15:29.794 --> 15:31.360
Emily Lopez on his behalf.

15:31.429 --> 15:33.730
Deputy District Attorney
Margaret Palmer for the People.

15:33.798 --> 15:35.665
Your Honor, I'm asking
to have my client evaluated

15:35.734 --> 15:37.400
for Mental Health Court
at the next available date.

15:37.469 --> 15:40.069
My client is
a decorated combat veteran

15:40.138 --> 15:41.404
who is suffering from PTSD.

15:41.473 --> 15:42.739
His actions are
a symptom of--

15:42.807 --> 15:43.873
Your Honor, the defendant
attacked a man.

15:43.942 --> 15:44.907
He needs treatment,
not further custody.

15:44.976 --> 15:46.242
He has two priors.
He's escalating.

15:46.311 --> 15:48.010
Your Honor, how many times
do we have

15:48.079 --> 15:50.046
ex-military defendants
standing before us?

15:50.115 --> 15:51.414
This is our chance
to address that.

15:51.483 --> 15:52.815
I'd like to speak to your client
directly, Ms. Lopez.

15:52.884 --> 15:54.684
Are you good with that?
Of course, Your Honor.

15:54.753 --> 15:55.818
[ whispers ] Stand up.

15:55.887 --> 15:58.087
Mr. Farrell,
your attorney has stated

15:58.156 --> 16:00.223
that you have
a PTSD diagnosis?

16:04.195 --> 16:05.561
Uh, yeah.

16:07.198 --> 16:08.664
Yes, Your Honor.

16:08.733 --> 16:11.000
As a result of your time
in the military?

16:11.069 --> 16:13.569
Can you tell me
a little bit about that?

16:19.711 --> 16:21.611
Helmand Province,

16:21.679 --> 16:23.613
outside of a town
called Sangin.

16:23.681 --> 16:26.616
The, uh...

16:26.684 --> 16:28.184
[ voice breaking ]
The APC I was riding in

16:28.253 --> 16:30.520
hit a roadside bomb,
flipped over.

16:30.588 --> 16:31.988
There...[ sniffles ]

16:35.527 --> 16:37.126
There were eight men.
[ sobs ]

16:38.797 --> 16:40.797
There were eight men
in the back.

16:40.865 --> 16:44.267
And...we were
trapped inside.

16:49.307 --> 16:51.274
It took 'em two hours
to dig us out.

16:54.245 --> 16:56.179
I was the only one
left alive.

16:57.816 --> 16:59.515
I...

17:02.554 --> 17:03.820
I...

17:03.888 --> 17:04.987
Thank you,

17:05.056 --> 17:06.422
Mr. Farrell,

17:06.491 --> 17:08.524
and thank you
for your service.

17:08.593 --> 17:09.992
Mm-hmm.

17:10.061 --> 17:13.196
Counsel, I'm going to
look into this.

17:13.264 --> 17:14.697
Recess.

17:17.769 --> 17:19.502
[ whispers ]

17:19.571 --> 17:25.708
♪♪♪

17:35.809 --> 17:37.008
His name is Tommy Farrell,
ex-military

17:37.077 --> 17:38.843
with combat-related PTSD.

17:38.912 --> 17:40.745
I think he's a candidate
for Mental Health Court.

17:40.814 --> 17:42.847
Long as he doesn't mind
waiting three months.

17:42.916 --> 17:44.515
I'm overwhelmed.
Look at this.

17:44.584 --> 17:46.718
My husband made this salad.
It comes with a manual.

17:46.786 --> 17:48.519
This guy's in custody
with no treatment.

17:48.588 --> 17:49.954
He can't wait
three months.

17:50.023 --> 17:51.756
- Do I owe you any favors?
- No.

17:51.825 --> 17:53.791
Then don't bother asking
to jump the queue.

17:53.860 --> 17:56.361
Honest to God, all I want
is a grilled cheese.

17:56.429 --> 17:58.196
Carmichael.

17:58.265 --> 18:00.732
We have a conversation
to finish.

18:05.905 --> 18:07.005
[ sighs ]

18:07.073 --> 18:09.574
Yes, I was a young,
ambitious lawyer,

18:09.643 --> 18:10.875
and I had
a strong suspicion

18:10.944 --> 18:13.144
that something hinky
was going on,

18:13.213 --> 18:14.379
and I chose not to look
any closer.

18:14.447 --> 18:17.248
I turned a blind eye
at first until I didn't,

18:17.317 --> 18:19.684
until I chose to fix it,
which is the point.
Fix it?

18:19.753 --> 18:21.919
I leaked the memo.
You waited almost a year.

18:21.988 --> 18:23.888
And Cuprillon Industries
went bankrupt.

18:23.957 --> 18:26.691
The two senior parents
responsible lost their jobs.

18:26.760 --> 18:28.926
I did the right thing, Lola.

18:28.995 --> 18:30.828
Here's what your opponent
is going to say.

18:30.897 --> 18:32.063
Too little, too late.

18:32.132 --> 18:33.431
While the lungs
of the workers

18:33.500 --> 18:36.067
were being destroyed,
you were fixing the game,

18:36.136 --> 18:37.502
suppressing a key memo.

18:37.570 --> 18:39.037
- I told you--
- Then to ease your conscience,

18:39.105 --> 18:40.371
you leaked the memo--

18:40.440 --> 18:42.340
a massive ethical violation.

18:42.409 --> 18:44.909
You breached your fiduciary
duty to your client.

18:44.978 --> 18:46.244
You violated a sacred trust

18:46.313 --> 18:48.212
that the entire legal system
is built on.

18:48.281 --> 18:51.516
Surely this is not who we need
as Attorney General.

18:53.453 --> 18:57.021
Is that my opponent talking?
Or you?

19:03.396 --> 19:05.463
[ door closes ]
Mark: Back away
like I told you?

19:05.532 --> 19:07.732
Can you tell me about it yet?
- Nope, never gonna tell you.

19:07.801 --> 19:09.067
And believe me,
you don't want to know.

19:09.135 --> 19:10.201
So it's getting worse.

19:10.270 --> 19:11.969
This whole
Teflon Mitch thing--

19:12.038 --> 19:13.471
you need to be careful,
Mark.

19:13.540 --> 19:14.539
And she changes
the subject.

19:14.607 --> 19:16.040
Wrongful convictions
are a big deal.

19:16.109 --> 19:17.842
What did Choi say?

19:17.911 --> 19:20.178
You haven't told him yet.

19:20.246 --> 19:22.180
Lola, if I'm even
in part responsible,

19:22.248 --> 19:23.881
You want to try
and fix it yourself.

19:23.950 --> 19:25.483
You would feel
exactly the same way.

19:25.552 --> 19:27.685
No! No, no, no.
The D.A. office

19:27.754 --> 19:30.154
has an entire unit--
the Conviction Review Unit.

19:30.223 --> 19:31.356
They'll take forever.

19:31.424 --> 19:33.257
Meanwhile,
this guy is sitting in prison.

19:33.326 --> 19:35.059
But he will get out,
Mark, thanks to you.

19:35.128 --> 19:36.361
I can get it done quicker.

19:36.429 --> 19:39.030
Wrongful convictions are messy.
They can get ugly.

19:39.099 --> 19:40.832
The Conviction Review Unit
is good,

19:40.900 --> 19:42.400
and you need
to protect yourself.

19:42.469 --> 19:44.268
- So do you, from Benner.
- I'm serious, Mark.

19:44.337 --> 19:46.270
You were one of the lawyers
responsible.

19:46.339 --> 19:48.306
Report it and back away.

19:50.744 --> 19:52.043
Last month, I filled in
a couple days

19:52.112 --> 19:54.679
for Campbell's court.
- I remember.

19:54.748 --> 19:56.381
This morning, I'm typing up
the transcript--

19:56.449 --> 19:58.449
Oh, wow. Look at this.

19:58.518 --> 19:59.684
Oh, that's Tommy?

19:59.753 --> 20:02.053
Before the thing--
that incident.

20:02.122 --> 20:03.755
He looks so young.

20:03.823 --> 20:06.758
Because there's no blood
or missing limbs,

20:06.826 --> 20:08.626
he doesn't see what happened
to him as an injury.

20:08.695 --> 20:10.595
I have cousins
in the military.

20:10.663 --> 20:12.797
Me, too. I have, like,
three different cousins.

20:12.866 --> 20:15.533
Tommy's a victim.
His crimes are symptoms,

20:15.602 --> 20:17.635
not a...
He's not a criminal.

20:17.704 --> 20:20.905
Anyway, the transcript--
did you find something?

20:20.974 --> 20:22.974
Charge to the jury.
He skipped over an entire--

20:23.042 --> 20:24.375
- Carol: I'm gonna strangle him.
- Carol!

20:24.444 --> 20:26.043
Then I'm gonna dismember him
with my bare hands.

20:26.112 --> 20:28.446
I need a psychiatrist.

20:28.515 --> 20:29.647
You and me both, sister.

20:29.716 --> 20:30.915
No, my A.D.--

20:30.984 --> 20:32.984
Barry's A.D.W.
I think he might actually--

20:33.052 --> 20:35.052
Uh, use Dr. Debbie.
She's really quite something.

20:36.523 --> 20:38.623
Sorry.
Campbell skipped over the--

20:38.691 --> 20:39.657
Uh, I'm getting called back
into court.

20:39.726 --> 20:43.060
[ cellphone buzzes ]
Me, too.

20:43.129 --> 20:44.429
I've looked into the options,

20:44.497 --> 20:46.464
and Mental Health Court
is not going to work.

20:46.533 --> 20:47.899
- There's a three-month wait.
- Your Honor--

20:47.967 --> 20:50.735
However, I am prepared
to entertain

20:50.804 --> 20:52.603
a defense motion
for mental health diversion

20:52.672 --> 20:56.073
under P.C. 1001.36,
right here in 802.

20:56.142 --> 20:59.210
Here? Now?
Your Honor, that's not--

20:59.279 --> 21:01.879
You were saying, counsel?

21:01.948 --> 21:03.548
Nope. Nothing.

21:03.616 --> 21:06.551
- Good. How long do you need--
- It's just normally

21:06.619 --> 21:08.052
anything involving violence
isn't diverted,

21:08.121 --> 21:10.087
given the public safety
concerns.

21:10.156 --> 21:13.224
Normally, yes. This time, no.

21:13.293 --> 21:16.627
Ms. Lopez, how long do you need
to get your client evaluated

21:16.696 --> 21:17.862
and prepare a motion?

21:17.931 --> 21:21.599
♪♪♪

21:21.668 --> 21:24.936
<i> Man on P.A.: [ indistinct ]</i>

21:25.004 --> 21:27.171
[ door buzzes and opens ]

21:30.844 --> 21:32.610
[ door buzzes ]

21:32.679 --> 21:34.645
Mr. Wardle, Mark Callan.

21:34.714 --> 21:37.148
I'm D.D.A., Los Angeles County.

21:37.217 --> 21:39.617
This is Samantha Powell,
Sergeant Krill.

21:39.686 --> 21:41.052
Guess it didn't work.

21:41.120 --> 21:42.954
- I'm sorry?
- Eight years praying

21:43.022 --> 21:44.422
something heavy would fall
on your head

21:44.491 --> 21:46.157
and crush you to death.

21:46.226 --> 21:47.592
- So you remember me, then.
- Why don't we sit down?

21:47.660 --> 21:49.327
Why don't you get
to the point?

21:51.130 --> 21:53.898
I've...been rereading
your file.

21:53.967 --> 21:55.566
- Really?
- At trial, you claimed

21:55.635 --> 21:57.635
you woke up when you heard
a struggle downstairs--

21:57.704 --> 22:00.371
voices shouting, a gunshot.
You went downstairs,

22:00.440 --> 22:01.873
found your brother
bleeding on the floor,

22:01.941 --> 22:03.441
and a man running
out the front door.

22:03.510 --> 22:05.676
At the time,
you said you got a clean look

22:05.745 --> 22:09.113
at the intruder's face.
It's eight years later.

22:09.182 --> 22:11.616
Think you'd
still recognize that man?

22:16.823 --> 22:18.356
Take your time.

22:25.532 --> 22:26.898
You're sure?

22:26.966 --> 22:29.367
That's the man
that killed my brother.

22:29.435 --> 22:34.805
♪♪♪

22:34.874 --> 22:36.807
He didn't hesitate
for a second.

22:36.876 --> 22:38.910
- Went right to Teflon Mitch.
- You showed him a six-pack?

22:38.978 --> 22:40.244
It's enough to charge him
right now.

22:40.313 --> 22:42.046
Once we charge him,
we collect his DNA.

22:42.115 --> 22:44.081
Did you bring the--
- There was DNA at the scene,

22:44.150 --> 22:46.217
on the victim's body
that never matched to anyone.

22:46.286 --> 22:47.385
We assumed
it wasn't connected,

22:47.453 --> 22:48.753
but if it's a match
for Teflon Mitch--

22:48.821 --> 22:50.221
Callan, I get it.

22:50.290 --> 22:51.489
If you put an innocent guy
in prison, that's upsetting.

22:51.558 --> 22:53.257
You know what I'm gonna say.
- Thomas, I--

22:53.326 --> 22:55.159
Follow protocol.
Write a transfer memo.

22:55.228 --> 22:57.228
Pass it on
to the Conviction Review Unit.

22:57.297 --> 22:59.096
The CRU will take forever.
It could take
how long it'll take.

22:59.165 --> 23:02.266
You have opened up a giant
freaking can of worms here.

23:02.335 --> 23:04.435
Every day that he sits
in prison is--
I agree.

23:04.504 --> 23:06.938
But we need to do this
by the book.

23:07.006 --> 23:08.472
Pass it on to the CRU.

23:17.483 --> 23:19.283
You want me to take
a first pass on the memo?

23:19.352 --> 23:21.018
You should work
on something else.

23:21.087 --> 23:22.253
Why?

23:22.322 --> 23:24.055
Because we're not
doing a memo.

23:24.123 --> 23:27.124
And you don't want to be
dragged into what happens next.

23:27.193 --> 23:30.094
♪♪♪

23:30.163 --> 23:31.796
This is good news, Tommy.

23:31.864 --> 23:34.465
If we can show that you're
suffering from PTSD

23:34.534 --> 23:35.566
and that is why
you got in that fight...

23:35.635 --> 23:37.068
- Uh-huh.
- And if the judge agrees,

23:37.136 --> 23:39.403
big "if,"
you won't go to prison.

23:39.472 --> 23:41.372
The court will press "pause"
on your case.

23:41.441 --> 23:43.140
You will go to treatment
instead,

23:43.209 --> 23:44.909
and if it's successful,
meaning if you stick with it,

23:44.978 --> 23:47.211
the charges disappear.
Case closed.

23:47.280 --> 23:49.213
Not really good
at talking about this.

23:49.282 --> 23:52.116
You need to get over it,
Tommy.

23:52.185 --> 23:54.251
You're gonna meet
with Dr. Debbie in a second.

23:54.320 --> 23:55.720
A shrink?
A therapist, yeah.

23:55.788 --> 23:57.388
She's gonna do an evaluation.

23:57.457 --> 23:58.656
The only thing, Tommy,
is the judge

23:58.725 --> 24:00.691
might speak to you again
in court.

24:00.760 --> 24:02.893
She might have more questions
about Afghanistan,

24:02.962 --> 24:04.362
about your trauma.

24:07.567 --> 24:10.501
I know this judge.
She will be more inclined

24:10.570 --> 24:12.003
to give you
the benefit of the doubt

24:12.071 --> 24:13.237
if you show her--
Yeah, okay.

24:13.306 --> 24:15.006
You've got a shot here,
Tommy,

24:15.074 --> 24:16.741
not just at staying
out of prison--

24:16.809 --> 24:19.677
of dealing with all
of the--your stuff.

24:19.746 --> 24:21.045
Why don't you just tell me
what to say,

24:21.114 --> 24:22.380
and I'll say it, all right?
Does that work?

24:22.448 --> 24:24.348
You wanna write it down
for me?

24:24.417 --> 24:29.553
♪♪♪

24:33.993 --> 24:35.259
[ door closes ]

24:35.328 --> 24:37.194
Luke?

24:37.263 --> 24:38.896
Tommy. Judge Campbell?

24:40.199 --> 24:42.266
I never found out what the--

24:42.335 --> 24:44.535
Oh, he made an error.
Instructions to the jury.

24:44.604 --> 24:45.770
He skipped a paragraph.

24:45.838 --> 24:48.072
- How big a--
- Grounds for mistrial.

24:48.141 --> 24:49.940
It's making me nauseous.

24:50.009 --> 24:52.977
Okay, okay. How about
you go to Judge Campbell,

24:53.046 --> 24:54.712
give him a heads up
that you saw it

24:54.781 --> 24:56.414
and that the lawyer might
see it, too, and then you--

24:56.482 --> 24:59.984
Ugh. I spent three days
in his courtroom,

25:00.053 --> 25:01.852
and he never spoke to me

25:01.921 --> 25:03.854
or looked at me.
Not once.

25:03.923 --> 25:04.989
Oof.

25:05.058 --> 25:06.357
The man scares me.

25:06.426 --> 25:07.692
Thank you.

25:07.760 --> 25:10.428
It's research on PTSD.
- Mm.

25:10.496 --> 25:12.163
Heartbreaking.

25:12.231 --> 25:13.497
When you have it,

25:13.566 --> 25:16.367
you can't remember the trauma
without reliving it.

25:16.436 --> 25:18.903
- That's so awful.
- There you are, just--

25:18.971 --> 25:20.705
You're just in some bar.

25:20.773 --> 25:22.907
Someone looks at you
a certain way,

25:22.975 --> 25:24.842
touches you by mistake,
and boom.

25:24.911 --> 25:29.113
All those feelings
and that fear...

25:29.182 --> 25:30.514
And anything
can trigger it--

25:30.583 --> 25:32.650
a sound, a smell.

25:34.187 --> 25:36.120
Three words?

25:38.691 --> 25:41.092
Yeah.

25:41.160 --> 25:43.060
And it all comes
rushing back.

25:43.129 --> 25:50.167
♪♪♪

25:59.184 --> 26:03.220
♪♪♪

26:03.288 --> 26:05.822
Look, I just have to say that
honestly, the whole concept

26:05.891 --> 26:07.124
of mental health diversion
eludes me.

26:07.192 --> 26:09.159
You are either responsible
for your actions,

26:09.228 --> 26:10.761
or you are legally insane.

26:10.829 --> 26:12.729
Not true.
Diminished actuality.

26:12.798 --> 26:14.097
Legal unconsciousness.

26:14.166 --> 26:15.966
It's an end run around,
actual criminal liability.

26:16.035 --> 26:18.468
You are nothing, Jonas,
if not predictable.

26:18.537 --> 26:20.837
There are reasons why this
defendant hasn't had treatment.

26:20.906 --> 26:22.906
- I agree with Judge Carmichael.
- No, you don't.

26:22.975 --> 26:24.441
- You do?
- These poor souls can't afford

26:24.510 --> 26:27.077
medication or doctors.
- Are you trying to get my goat?

26:27.146 --> 26:30.280
Well, perhaps, if we lived
in Canada or Sweden,

26:30.349 --> 26:32.449
maybe then we wouldn't have
this epidemic of the untreated.

26:32.518 --> 26:34.851
- That's exactly right.
- 40% of the prison population

26:34.920 --> 26:37.320
has mental health issues.
- 46.

26:37.389 --> 26:39.523
- How many of them are veterans?
- More than is comfortable.

26:39.591 --> 26:42.092
No, the system is not working,
my young friend,

26:42.161 --> 26:45.195
and why shouldn't the judiciary
take the lead?

26:45.264 --> 26:46.797
I'll tell you exactly why
and at some length.

26:46.865 --> 26:48.131
It's not worth the risk,
that's why.

26:48.200 --> 26:50.634
What if he reoffends?
Another bar fight,

26:50.702 --> 26:52.536
except this time
he kills somebody?

26:52.604 --> 26:55.105
Who wants that
on their conscience...again?

27:01.980 --> 27:03.647
That was a cheap shot.

27:03.715 --> 27:05.248
Of course.
I know. I apologize.

27:05.317 --> 27:07.751
Travis Bolson is
a completely different--

27:07.820 --> 27:08.919
Except that it
really isn't.

27:08.987 --> 27:10.120
- Isn't what?
- That different.

27:10.189 --> 27:12.155
And the only reason
Maggie Palmer

27:12.224 --> 27:14.791
isn't bludgeoning you with it
is because she's sucking up.

27:14.860 --> 27:16.660
If I choose
to trust a defendant--

27:16.728 --> 27:18.662
Oh, I find it fascinating,
Carmichael,

27:18.730 --> 27:21.398
who you choose to trust
and who you choose to judge.

27:24.736 --> 27:26.069
You think I'm judging you?

27:26.138 --> 27:28.405
What else
would you call it?
You asked me.

27:28.474 --> 27:30.273
I made a mistake,
and I fixed it.

27:30.342 --> 27:31.908
No, you didn't.
Stop saying you fixed it.

27:31.977 --> 27:33.610
Why can't you give me
the benefit of--

27:33.679 --> 27:36.813
You came to me.
You asked me to dig around.

27:36.882 --> 27:39.082
You must have known that I
would find all of this.

27:39.151 --> 27:40.450
I could make
a genuine difference.

27:40.519 --> 27:42.853
You know that I could.
That is not the issue here.

27:42.921 --> 27:44.254
Yes, it is.

27:44.323 --> 27:45.755
Everything
that we stand for--

27:45.824 --> 27:47.157
all the change that you
want to see happen.

27:47.226 --> 27:49.159
Don't do that.
Sentencing reform,

27:49.228 --> 27:51.328
diversion program.
Lisa.

27:51.396 --> 27:52.195
I want you to be a part
of it, Carmichael,

27:52.264 --> 27:54.331
all of it,
a part of my team.

27:54.399 --> 27:56.299
In exchange for what?
Keeping your secret?

27:56.368 --> 27:57.767
Defending you
when this comes out?

27:57.836 --> 27:59.236
And how is that
gonna look in the press?

27:59.304 --> 28:02.305
Not one but two sitting judges
saying that it is okay

28:02.374 --> 28:05.142
to break attorney--
No one is going to
ask you to--

28:05.210 --> 28:08.145
You violated your duty of
loyalty to your client, Lisa.

28:08.213 --> 28:10.747
<i> You</i> did that, and<i> you</i>
should have been disbarred.

28:10.816 --> 28:13.216
And now I could be disbarred
for not reporting it.

28:13.285 --> 28:15.118
I think that you're
overstating your--

28:15.187 --> 28:17.988
I don't think I am.

28:18.056 --> 28:20.323
Your good intentions
don't matter.

28:20.392 --> 28:23.126
The right thing--
it doesn't matter.

28:23.195 --> 28:24.794
Not in this case.
It really doesn't,

28:24.863 --> 28:28.265
even if we both wish
that it did.

28:28.333 --> 28:44.281
♪♪♪

28:46.585 --> 28:48.251
Bet I can handle this.
[ laughs ]

28:48.320 --> 28:50.987
What are you doing here?
You're off the case, Sam.

28:51.056 --> 28:53.023
Do not sit down.

28:53.091 --> 28:54.925
Is Douglas Wardle
innocent or not?

28:54.993 --> 28:56.326
Answer the question.

28:56.395 --> 28:57.627
Yes.

28:57.696 --> 29:00.130
Then you're gonna fix it,
and I got your back.

29:01.433 --> 29:02.699
All rise.

29:02.768 --> 29:04.768
Department 61 of
the Los Angeles Superior Court

29:04.836 --> 29:07.871
is now in session.
Judge Jonas Laski presiding.

29:07.940 --> 29:10.140
All right, Mr. Callan,
if you're sufficiently healthy,

29:10.209 --> 29:11.241
we can get this thing
back on the rails.

29:11.310 --> 29:12.375
Let's get the jury in here.

29:12.444 --> 29:13.643
Your Honor, the People move

29:13.712 --> 29:15.245
to dismiss the charges
in this case

29:15.314 --> 29:17.247
under Penal Code
section 1385.

29:17.316 --> 29:18.648
- Wait. What?
- Really?

29:18.717 --> 29:20.083
The People aren't confident

29:20.152 --> 29:22.419
that we can prove this case
beyond a reasonable doubt.

29:22.487 --> 29:24.521
No argument here,
Your Honor.

29:26.725 --> 29:28.425
Okey-doke.

29:28.493 --> 29:29.793
Motion granted.

29:29.861 --> 29:30.894
Case dismissed.

29:30.963 --> 29:31.995
Yes.

29:32.064 --> 29:34.231
[ indistinct chatter ]

29:37.035 --> 29:38.702
Detective?

29:40.072 --> 29:41.238
Mitchell Sanderly,
you're under arrest

29:41.306 --> 29:42.839
for the murder of Troy Wardle.

29:42.908 --> 29:44.841
Whoa! Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa. What the hell, Callan?

29:44.910 --> 29:46.810
New evidence has come
to light, Your Honor--

29:46.878 --> 29:48.511
enough to make an arrest.
You're gonna do this
in the middle of the courtroom?

29:48.580 --> 29:49.946
I have a warrant
for a buccal swab.

29:50.015 --> 29:51.448
We're gonna go ahead and harvest
the DNA of your client.

29:51.516 --> 29:52.983
This is because you were losing.
[ gavel banging ]

29:53.051 --> 29:55.151
Go! Get him outta here.
Go! Get him out!
All right.

29:55.220 --> 29:56.386
[ exhales deeply ]

30:00.592 --> 30:02.959
Poor Mitch. He's gonna need
a new nickname.

30:07.099 --> 30:08.431
[ exhales deeply ]

30:08.500 --> 30:12.202
It's called hyperarousal.
Patients are reckless,

30:12.271 --> 30:15.038
self-destructive,
aggressive outbursts.

30:15.107 --> 30:16.906
In your opinion,
is there a connection

30:16.975 --> 30:19.743
between the alleged crime
and a diagnosis of PTSD?

30:19.811 --> 30:20.710
A direct connection.

30:20.779 --> 30:24.948
Tommy's PTSD
causes hyperarousal.

30:25.017 --> 30:26.283
In this case, that is
exactly what happened

30:26.351 --> 30:27.684
the night of the bar fight.

30:27.753 --> 30:29.919
And what impact would treatment
have on my client?

30:29.988 --> 30:32.122
Tommy's aggressive behavior
would stop.

30:32.190 --> 30:34.691
Thank you, doctor.

30:34.760 --> 30:37.027
Ms. Palmer, any questions?

30:37.095 --> 30:40.030
Has PTSD robbed Tommy
of his faculties?

30:40.098 --> 30:41.898
I'm sorry. I don't
understand the question.

30:41.967 --> 30:43.733
Does it make him hallucinate?
Does he know who he is?

30:43.802 --> 30:46.970
Where he is?
Who he's talking to?
Yes.

30:47.039 --> 30:48.405
Is he capable
of making choices, doctor?

30:48.473 --> 30:50.106
For example, the choice
of whether or not

30:50.175 --> 30:52.542
to attack someone with a bottle.
- Objection, Your Honor.

30:52.611 --> 30:54.644
Inflammatory.
Overruled. Careful, Ms. Palmer.

30:54.713 --> 30:56.980
Of course he does. PTSD--

30:57.049 --> 30:58.848
Doctor, if Tommy
goes into treatment,

30:58.917 --> 31:01.885
if he receives medication,
it's still possible

31:01.953 --> 31:04.254
that he will reoffend,
is it not?

31:04.323 --> 31:05.855
There's always a risk.
Could he kill someone,
doctor?

31:05.924 --> 31:07.390
Objection.
Calls for speculation.

31:07.459 --> 31:08.892
I'm simply trying
to establish whether--
Sustained.

31:08.960 --> 31:11.161
That's enough, Ms. Palmer.

31:12.531 --> 31:14.097
Thank you, doctor.
Nothing further.

31:14.166 --> 31:16.966
The witness may step down.

31:21.873 --> 31:23.940
Your Honor, we've outlined
a treatment plan--

31:24.009 --> 31:26.576
Yes, thank you, counsel.
I've read it.

31:28.180 --> 31:29.612
[ clears throat ]

31:31.783 --> 31:32.916
Your Honor?

31:36.121 --> 31:37.687
And why should I believe
that you're committed

31:37.756 --> 31:39.456
to this treatment,
Mr. Farrell?

31:43.929 --> 31:46.463
Your Honor, if I could have
just one minute?

31:46.531 --> 31:47.897
One minute.

31:50.902 --> 31:52.836
Tommy, look at me. Tommy.

31:54.573 --> 31:56.039
Ever since you've come back,

31:56.108 --> 31:59.976
you have been running
from what happened.

32:00.045 --> 32:06.316
And you have to stop
and turn and face it...

32:06.385 --> 32:08.284
now.

32:25.504 --> 32:27.103
If you'd asked me last week,

32:27.172 --> 32:30.840
I'd have said I don't need
a doctor or treatment.

32:30.909 --> 32:32.575
I need a job.

32:34.045 --> 32:40.617
You know, everyone always says
"Move on," so...I tried.

32:40.685 --> 32:42.786
I did.

32:42.854 --> 32:44.988
But...

32:45.056 --> 32:47.657
it's not working right.

32:47.726 --> 32:51.728
And this feels like this...

32:51.797 --> 32:55.165
really feels like
this could be...a chance to...

33:00.205 --> 33:05.074
I want to get better,
Your Honor.

33:22.727 --> 33:25.195
Um, Judge Campbell,
the instructions to the jury--

33:25.263 --> 33:26.763
you left out a paragraph.

33:26.832 --> 33:29.098
The Union
of Act and Intent provision

33:29.167 --> 33:31.634
per Penal Code section 20.
My dear, I am sure
you're mistaken.

33:31.703 --> 33:34.871
Sir--
I've never done anything
remotely like that in my life.

33:34.940 --> 33:36.706
I appreciate that, sir,
but this time--

33:36.775 --> 33:39.843
Young lady, your transcription
is incorrect.

33:39.911 --> 33:41.377
All right?
The error is yours.

33:41.446 --> 33:43.680
Now perhaps we can both of us
can get back to work here.

33:43.748 --> 33:45.148
It's Ms. Castillo.

33:46.218 --> 33:47.383
Excuse me?

33:47.452 --> 33:49.452
Or, uh, Sara, if you must,

33:49.521 --> 33:52.355
but not "young lady"
and not "my dear."

33:52.424 --> 33:54.991
Now, it is unlikely that I
would miss a single word.

33:55.060 --> 33:56.626
The notion that I could

33:56.695 --> 33:58.595
miss an entire paragraph
is laughable.

33:58.663 --> 34:00.763
I mean,
I don't make mistakes.

34:00.832 --> 34:03.633
Now, sir, you give
these instructions every day.

34:03.702 --> 34:06.402
You went on autopilot
for a split second.

34:06.471 --> 34:08.838
Judges have been known
to skip an entire page.

34:08.907 --> 34:10.673
Now I had the courtesy
to let you know.

34:10.742 --> 34:12.976
I'd appreciate
if you had the courtesy

34:13.044 --> 34:15.245
to treat me
as a professional.

34:19.417 --> 34:21.284
Stop!

34:22.821 --> 34:24.487
You're right.

34:24.556 --> 34:27.690
Ms. Castillo, I do apologize.
That was impertinent.

34:27.759 --> 34:30.326
If it was my error
and it's exposed,

34:30.395 --> 34:32.929
I will pay
that particular piper.

34:32.998 --> 34:34.163
Thank you.

34:34.232 --> 34:37.200
If you'd ever like
to change judges,

34:37.269 --> 34:39.702
you come find me.

34:45.443 --> 34:47.610
The defendant Tommy

34:47.679 --> 34:49.812
stands there in front of me
making promises,

34:49.881 --> 34:53.116
and I want for him
to be better, to succeed.

34:53.184 --> 34:55.018
I ache for him
for what he's been through.

34:55.086 --> 34:56.286
But at the same time,

34:56.354 --> 34:58.588
I have a responsibility
to the man that he hurt,

34:58.657 --> 35:00.590
to the people
he could hurt next.

35:00.659 --> 35:02.058
That's the job.
I know it's the job.

35:02.127 --> 35:03.826
I just have to...
Grapple.

35:03.895 --> 35:05.795
Grapple! I am grappling.

35:05.864 --> 35:08.131
You're a grappler.
Grappler.

35:08.199 --> 35:11.634
So Judge Benner leaked
the memo

35:11.703 --> 35:13.136
that brought
Cuprillon down.

35:13.204 --> 35:14.837
When you were fighting,
I was listening at the door.

35:14.906 --> 35:16.506
Sherri, you can't--
Get over it.
I shouldn't have to.

35:16.575 --> 35:19.943
If I'm gonna protect you,
you need to tell me things.

35:20.011 --> 35:21.277
It's not your job
to protect me.

35:21.346 --> 35:23.413
Now, Tommy--pros and cons.

35:23.481 --> 35:25.481
Let's talk it out.
I will tell you what to do,

35:25.550 --> 35:28.585
at which point you will proceed
to do the exact opposite.

35:33.224 --> 35:34.991
What are you doing here?

35:35.060 --> 35:36.826
Sorry for just showing up.
I should have texted.

35:36.895 --> 35:38.795
That's okay. I was working.
I'm so behind.

35:38.863 --> 35:40.763
I just thought if I asked
if I could come over,

35:40.832 --> 35:43.633
you'd probably say no.

35:43.702 --> 35:45.935
So listen--
I've been avoiding you.
I'm sorry.

35:46.004 --> 35:47.303
It's okay.
It's incredibly awkward

35:47.372 --> 35:49.472
working in the same courtroom.
- That's not why--

35:49.541 --> 35:50.974
And obviously we can't
discuss the case.

35:51.042 --> 35:52.308
I've been running away.
That's why we haven't talked--

35:52.377 --> 35:53.876
It's okay.
Not from you.

35:53.945 --> 35:55.211
From what you said,
and that's not fair.

35:55.280 --> 35:57.213
We don't have to talk about it.
That's not why I'm here.

35:58.617 --> 36:00.483
I have a question for you.

36:00.552 --> 36:01.951
What?

36:02.020 --> 36:04.220
If you could only eat pizza
for the rest of your life,

36:04.289 --> 36:08.424
every meal, or only eat fries,
which would it be?

36:08.493 --> 36:09.759
Take your time.

36:09.828 --> 36:11.628
That's easy. Pizza.
Multiple food groups.

36:11.696 --> 36:14.831
Yeah. If you had to lose
your arms or your legs...

36:14.899 --> 36:16.399
- Legs.
- Mm!

36:16.468 --> 36:19.002
[ laughs ]
Uh, no books or no music
for the rest of your life?

36:19.070 --> 36:21.504
Oh, that's a good one.

36:21.573 --> 36:22.505
Mm-hmm.

36:22.574 --> 36:24.073
- Oh,<i> damn.</i>
- Mm.

36:24.142 --> 36:26.175
Huh.

36:26.244 --> 36:27.343
Hmm.

36:28.413 --> 36:30.880
Mmm. Mmm. [ laughs ]

36:34.563 --> 36:36.997
This entire diversion exercise
is ill-advised.

36:37.066 --> 36:38.399
Carmichael's trying
to force me to--

36:38.467 --> 36:39.833
The kid is a repeat violent.

36:39.902 --> 36:41.769
He needs to go to prison
for many years.

36:41.837 --> 36:44.939
I forget. When did you
serve in uniform?

36:45.007 --> 36:46.674
When did you see combat?
Excuse me?

36:46.742 --> 36:48.275
I mean, do you think
maybe it's possible

36:48.344 --> 36:49.576
that different rules
apply in this case,

36:49.645 --> 36:51.545
given who Tommy is
and what he's done?

36:51.614 --> 36:53.047
Maybe having a little bit
of compassion,

36:53.115 --> 36:55.883
looking beyond the obvious
and addressing the real problem?

36:55.952 --> 36:57.051
And keeping this guy
out of custody

36:57.119 --> 36:58.519
isn't such a crazy idea.

36:58.587 --> 37:00.955
- I'm looking for Mark Callan.
- He's right there.

37:03.092 --> 37:05.192
You're wrong,
and I'm gonna tell you why.

37:05.261 --> 37:07.695
I'm sure you are.

37:07.763 --> 37:09.196
Rhonda McRhonda.

37:09.265 --> 37:11.799
Quite the spectacle, Callan.
Are you pleased with yourself?

37:11.867 --> 37:12.800
Ready to cut a deal?

37:12.868 --> 37:15.002
Ms. McReady, Thomas Choi.

37:15.071 --> 37:16.470
Uh, we could talk
in my office.

37:16.539 --> 37:18.238
Samantha,
if you wouldn't mind?

37:18.307 --> 37:21.241
Hi, uh, yeah.
Just through here.

37:23.946 --> 37:26.680
I told you to leave it alone,
and you didn't.

37:26.749 --> 37:28.315
- I know, but--
- You were showboating.

37:28.384 --> 37:30.017
We put an innocent man
in jail.

37:30.086 --> 37:32.019
And we have a process
to deal with that.

37:32.088 --> 37:33.921
It would have taken them
months, years.

37:33.990 --> 37:35.389
For good reason--

37:35.458 --> 37:37.324
so that we don't
screw it up again.

37:37.393 --> 37:39.860
[ sighs ]
Look, when you pull
this kind of crap--

37:39.929 --> 37:41.729
Thomas.
I gave you a direct order,
and you ignored it.

37:41.797 --> 37:43.931
I am sending you home.

37:44.000 --> 37:46.300
I'm serious. Pack your stuff.
You're benched.

37:47.903 --> 37:49.269
We'll talk tomorrow.

37:49.338 --> 37:53.407
♪♪♪

37:53.476 --> 37:56.643
Mr. Farrell, I am satisfied
that you wish to get treatment

37:56.712 --> 38:00.014
and have little doubt that you
would benefit from it.

38:00.082 --> 38:04.952
However, I am responsible
to the public and to its safety.

38:05.021 --> 38:07.855
The defense's motion
is denied,

38:07.923 --> 38:11.158
which means we return
to trial unless...

38:12.261 --> 38:13.794
I am prepared to mandate

38:13.863 --> 38:15.629
treatment for the accused
while in custody

38:15.698 --> 38:17.965
and monitor it
with biweekly updates

38:18.034 --> 38:20.801
if you are able
to come to terms.

38:26.142 --> 38:28.175
[ whispers ] She's talking
about a guilty plea.

38:28.244 --> 38:29.543
We should consider it,
Tommy,

38:29.612 --> 38:32.112
if they're willing
to reduce the charge.

38:33.049 --> 38:34.515
[ lowered voice ] Drop it
down to a misdemeanor.

38:34.583 --> 38:36.550
Get rid of the strike.
If you want to get back

38:36.619 --> 38:39.353
in Carmichael's good books,
this is how.

38:46.896 --> 38:49.196
Your Honor, if the defendant
is willing to plead guilty,

38:49.265 --> 38:51.265
the People are prepared
to drop the charge

38:51.333 --> 38:52.766
to misdemeanor assault,
no strike,

38:52.835 --> 38:55.369
one year in county jail...

38:55.438 --> 38:56.970
with treatment.

39:07.083 --> 39:08.682
Your Honor, I think
we can make this work.

39:08.751 --> 39:21.695
♪♪♪

39:21.764 --> 39:23.831
That's why you should
keep your distance.

39:23.899 --> 39:25.666
You're gonna be in trouble
with Choi now, too.

39:27.436 --> 39:31.004
You taught me something
with this case.

39:31.073 --> 39:33.674
Eight years ago,
when Douglas was testifying,

39:33.742 --> 39:35.809
when you were
convicting him,

39:35.878 --> 39:37.811
was there a voice
in your head telling you

39:37.880 --> 39:39.079
something's not right?

39:39.148 --> 39:40.981
[ sighs ]

39:45.454 --> 39:48.021
Listen to that voice,
even if it's inconvenient,

39:48.090 --> 39:50.691
even if it gets you
in trouble.

39:50.759 --> 39:52.359
That's what you taught me.

39:52.428 --> 40:08.375
♪♪♪

40:24.827 --> 40:29.396
For 30 years,
I've been asking myself,

40:29.465 --> 40:35.702
did I do enough?
Did I absolve myself?

40:35.771 --> 40:37.538
Am I free to go?

40:37.606 --> 40:39.706
You're right. [ sighs ]

40:39.775 --> 40:43.544
I wanted you to find out
and pardon me.

40:43.612 --> 40:46.380
And as much as I hate
your verdict,

40:46.448 --> 40:48.382
I can't argue with it.

40:51.120 --> 40:53.420
I'm withdrawing from
the Attorney General race.

40:53.489 --> 40:56.156
I appreciate you taking
the time to help me

40:56.225 --> 41:01.495
sort through all of this,
so we can...

41:01.564 --> 41:05.265
Now we can both get
back to work. Right?

41:07.836 --> 41:09.870
Now we can get back to work.

41:09.939 --> 41:18.445
♪♪♪

41:18.514 --> 41:21.281
♪<i> Lost in the fog</i> ♪

41:21.350 --> 41:24.184
♪<i> It's hollow here</i> ♪

41:24.253 --> 41:27.521
♪<i> Blood running hot</i> ♪

41:27.590 --> 41:29.923
Hi. You got my text.

41:29.992 --> 41:31.592
- You okay?
- I'm fine. I'm just--

41:31.660 --> 41:33.393
I'm gonna be working here
for a couple more hours,

41:33.462 --> 41:35.629
just wanted you to know.

41:35.698 --> 41:37.264
Oh, you can't
just walk in here.

41:37.333 --> 41:39.600
You work for the D.A.,
remember?
I wanted to say good night.

41:39.668 --> 41:41.435
Mm-hmm. Good night.

41:41.503 --> 41:42.903
Your desk is worse
than mine.

41:42.972 --> 41:45.205
Mm. Barry's the gift
that keeps on giving.

41:45.274 --> 41:48.909
I spent all day on his files.
Now mine are in crisis.

41:48.978 --> 41:50.611
Mm, it's a weird couple
of days.

41:50.679 --> 41:53.113
Because of the three
unfortunate words?

41:53.182 --> 41:55.148
I took those back,
remember?

41:55.217 --> 41:57.150
'Cause of the trial? You were
pretty quiet over there

41:57.219 --> 41:58.719
at the prosecution table.

41:58.787 --> 42:01.221
The worst thing about Maggie
is how certain she was,

42:01.290 --> 42:02.556
every time she opened
her mouth.

42:02.625 --> 42:04.992
That kind of certainty
creeps me out.

42:05.060 --> 42:07.261
You know what I respect?
The not knowing,

42:07.329 --> 42:11.064
the struggle, the doubt.

42:11.133 --> 42:15.602
Anyway, I should...
let you get back to work.

42:17.006 --> 42:18.805
I love you, too.

42:20.676 --> 42:21.942
I think.

42:23.612 --> 42:27.214
I'm not entirely sure,
but it is possible.

42:28.951 --> 42:31.351
It's the best I can do.

42:33.155 --> 42:34.221
I'll take it.

42:34.290 --> 42:36.089
- Hmm?
- Mm-hmm.

42:36.158 --> 42:39.893
♪<i> I hear its sad song</i> ♪

42:48.837 --> 42:55.175
♪♪♪
